    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#000000">Strategy</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><br />
Strategy:<br />
 The main strategy for this deck is to bid high (between 4 and 6) so you can go out in front and control the twilight pool preventing your opponent from deploying large minions.<br />
<br />
<br />
The Fellowship:<br />
 In case of a win, I&#39;ll have Arwen and Sam (for burdens removal) and will pick up Aragorn with &quot;The Prancing Poney&quot;. Later on, I&#39;ll sacrifice Sam to a minion so I can control the twilight pool.<br />
<br />
 If I loose, I&#39;ll start up with Boromir and Merry avoiding Gondor cards to burn in my hand :-) Also I have some (not many --but all I could get) Nazguls to delay opponents fellowship a bit :-)<br />
<br />
<br />
Drawbacks:<br />
 One of the main problems with this deck are Isengard conditions.. Anyone has any idea on how to change it to avoid this main disadvantage?<br />
 One other thing is that sometimes I end up games with only one &quot;No Stranger to the Shadows&quot; deployed from main deck.. Anyone thinks I should change my shadow to Moria? My Moria minions aren&#39;t that good (don&#39;t have any Cave Troll).. but still it would speed up my &quot;hand renewal&quot;..<br />
<br />
 If you have any idea/opinion about this deck I would love to hear it.. </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#000000"> </Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">DeckTech <BR> For the Players, By the Players  <BR>www.decktech.net </FONT></TD></TR></table> 
